{{Infobox California Supreme Court case |Litigants=Curran v. Mount Diablo Council of the Boy Scouts of America |ArgueDate= |ArgueYear= |DecideDate=March 23 |DecideYear=1998 |FullName=Timothy Curran v. Mount Diablo Council of the Boy Scouts of America |Citations={{law report|17|Cal.4th|670}}, 952 P.2d 218, 72 Cal.Rptr.2d 410 (1998) |Prior=Judgment affirmed, 147 Cal.App.3d 712, 195 Cal. Rptr. 325 (1983) |Subsequent= |Holding=The Boy Scouts of America are not considered a "business establishment" and do not fall under the provisions of California's Unruh Civil Rights Act. Decision of the Court of Appeal is affirmed. |ChiefJudge=[[Ronald M. George]] |AssociateJudges=[[Stanley Mosk]], [[Joyce L. Kennard]], [[Marvin R. Baxter]], [[Kathryn Werdegar]], [[Ming Chin]], [[Janice Rogers Brown]] |Majority=George |JoinMajority=Kennard, Baxter, Chin |Concurrence=Mosk |Concurrence2=Kennard |Concurrence3=Werdegar |Concurrence4=Brown |LawsApplied=[[Unruh Civil Rights Act]] ([[California Civil Code|Cal. Civil Code]] § 51) }} {{italic title|force=true}} '''''Curran v. Mount Diablo Council of the Boy Scouts of America''''', 17 Cal.4th 670, 952 P.2d 218, 72 Cal.Rptr.2d 410 (1998), was a landmark case which upheld the right of a private organization in [[California]] to not allow new members on the basis of their [[sexual orientation]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=Timothy Curran v. Mount Diablo Council of the Boy Scouts of America |date=March 23, 1998 |publisher=Supreme Court of California |url=http://caselaw.lp.findlaw.com/data2/californiastatecases/s039738.pdf }}</ref> Its [[companion case]] was ''[[Randall v. Orange County Council]]'', 17 Cal.4th 736, 952 P.2d 261, 72 Cal.Rptr.2d 453 (1998).
==Background== In 1980, eighteen-year-old Tim Curran, an [[Eagle Scout rank (Boy Scouts of America)|Eagle Scout]], applied to be an assistant Scoutmaster in the [[Mount Diablo Council]] [[Boy Scouts of America]]. Members of the Boy Scouts of America, however, had recently learned that Curran was [[homosexuality|gay]] after reading an [[Oakland Tribune]] article on gay youth which featured an interview with Curran. Based on his sexual orientation, the Boy Scouts of America refused to allow Curran to hold a leadership position in their organization.
Curran sued in 1981, alleging that the Boy Scouts of America's membership requirements amounted to unlawful discrimination under California's [[Unruh Civil Rights Act]], which required "Full and equal accommodations, advantages, facilities, privileges or services in all business establishments".
==Decision== This case was ultimately decided in 1998, when the [[California Supreme Court]] ruled in favor of the Boy Scouts of America. The court held that because the Boy Scouts of America was not considered a “business establishment” under the Unruh Civil Rights Act, it could not be required to change its membership policies so as to include homosexuals.
Psychiatrist and lawyer [[Richard Green (sexologist)|Richard Green]] was co-counsel for Curran.<ref>{{cite book|last1=West|first1=Donald James|last2=Green|first2=Richard |title=Sociolegal Control of Homosexuality: A Multi-nation Comparison|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AwD3FNUJjXwC&pg=PA152|year=1997|publisher=Plenum|location=New York|isbn=0-306-45532-3|page=152}}</ref>
{{Portal|Scouting}}
